In algebra, the '''Mori–Nagata theorem''' introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Mori|first=Yoshiro|authorlink=Yoshiro Mori (mathematician)|year=1953}} and {{harvs|txt|last=Nagata|authorlink=Masayoshi Nagata|year=1955}}, states the following: let ''A'' be a [[noetherian ring|noetherian]] [[reduced ring|reduced]] [[commutative ring]] with the [[total ring of fractions]] ''K''. Then the [[integral closure]] of ''A'' in ''K'' is a [[direct product]] of ''r'' [[Krull domain]]s, where ''r'' is the number of [[minimal prime ideal]]s of ''A''.

The theorem is a partial generalization of the [[Krull–Akizuki theorem]], which concerns a one-dimensional noetherian domain. A consequence of the theorem is that if ''R'' is a [[Nagata ring]], then every ''R''-subalgebra of finite type is again a Nagata ring {{harv|Nishimura|1976}}.

The Mori–Nagata theorem follows from [[Matijevic's theorem]].<ref>{{citation |title=Review: David Rees, Lectures on the asymptotic theory of ideals |last1=McAdam |first1=S. |url=http://projecteuclid.org/DPubS?verb=Display&version=1.0&service=UI&handle=euclid.bams/1183555628&page=record |journal=Bull. Amer. Math. Soc. (N.S.) |volume=22 |issue=2 |year=1990 |pages=315–317 |doi=10.1090/s0273-0979-1990-15896-3 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514134038/http://projecteuclid.org/DPubS?verb=Display&version=1.0&service=UI&handle=euclid.bams%2F1183555628&page=record |archivedate=2014-05-14 |df= }}</ref>

