{{Other uses|Chasles' theorem (disambiguation)}}
In [[algebraic geometry]], '''Chasles' theorem''' says that if two pencils of curves have no curves in common, then the intersections of those curves form another [[pencil of curves]] the degree of which can be calculated from the degrees of the initial two pencils.<ref>{{mathworld | title = Chasles's Theorem | urlname = ChaslessTheorem}}</ref>

The result is attributed to [[Michel Chasles]] (1793–1880).

