In [[algebraic geometry]], the '''Kempf–Ness theorem''', introduced by {{harvs|txt|last1=Kempf|author1-link=George Kempf|last2=Ness|year=1979}}, gives a criterion for the [[Geometric invariant theory#Stability|stability]] of a vector in a [[group representation|representation]] of a complex [[reductive group]]. If the [[complex number|complex]] [[vector space]] is given a [[Norm (mathematics)|norm]] that is [[Invariant (mathematics)|invariant]] under a [[maximal compact subgroup]] of the reductive group, then the Kempf–Ness theorem states that a vector is stable if and only if the norm attains a minimum value on the [[Group action (mathematics)|orbit]] of the vector.

