In [[algebraic geometry]], '''Nagata's compactification theorem''', introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Nagata|year1=1962|year2=1963|authorlink=Masayoshi Nagata}}, implies that every [[abstract variety]] can be embedded in a [[complete variety]], and more generally shows that a [[Glossary of scheme theory#separated|separated]] and [[Finite morphism#Morphisms of finite type|finite type morphism]] to a [[Noetherian scheme]] ''S'' can be factored into an [[Glossary of scheme theory#immersion|open immersion]] followed by a [[Proper morphism|proper mapping]]. 

Nagata's original proof used the older terminology of [[Zariski–Riemann space]]s and [[Valuation (algebra)|valuation theory]], which sometimes made it hard to follow.
[[Pierre Deligne|Deligne]] showed, in unpublished notes expounded by [[Brian Conrad|Conrad]], that Nagata's proof can be translated into scheme theory and that the condition that ''S'' is Noetherian can be replaced by the much weaker condition that ''S'' is [[Compact space|quasi-compact]] and quasi-separated. {{harvtxt|Lütkebohmert|1993}} gave another scheme-theoretic proof of Nagata's theorem.

An important application of Nagata's theorem is in defining the analogue in algebraic geometry of [[cohomology with compact support]], or more generally higher direct image functors with proper support.

